result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

cases #14CM262 and #14CF244 called at 10:04am. [MK]
Defendant Steven T. Delap appears via videoconferencing from Green Bay Correctional Institution. His standby-counsel, Attorney Karl Huebner, is present in the courtroom.  ADA Jeffrey Shock appears for the State of Wisconsin.  
Captain P. Wallace (Jefferson County Sheriff's Office) is present. 
On agreement of counsel, the Court finds that the videoconferencing system is sight and sound sufficient. 


The Court addresses restitution in Case #14CM262:
Steven Delap- sworn & testifies
--testimony given by Mr. Delap
--examination by the Court
Captain Paul Wallace- sworn & testifies
--direct examination by ADA Shock
--State's Exh. #1: invoice from Worthington Direct for purchase of cabinets

Based on testimony and on the agreement of the parties, the Court finds that the restitution amount due in Case #14CM262 consists of:  
$755.55 for cabinets (calculation: three cabinets at $349.95 each= $1049.85, minus $225 credit for the shipping-damage deduction on new cabinets, minus credit of $69.30 for the scrap metal disposal of old cabinets) 
$128.85 for workbooks 
$29.90 for damaged headsets
$100 for ten hours of labor at $10 per hour
$150.99 portion of cost for shipping of cabinets

Therefore, the Court orders payment of $1165.29 in restitution as a condition of Probation, with $100 payable to the Jefferson County Literacy Council, and the remainder [$1065.29] payable to the Jefferson County Sheriff's Office.  The payment of the 10% restitution processing fee applies. 
 
Mr. Delap requests that the Court set the maximum of 10% for prison wage withdrawl.  
After hearing arguments from ADA Shock and Mr. Delap on this request, the Court designates that the DOC is authorized to deduct up to 25 percent of prison wages for the purpose of payment of restitution. 
--------------------------------------------------
The Court addresses the Sentence-Credit Request: 
--Mr. Delap seeks time for the dates from 7/17/14 until 12/2/12; this would be 166 days
--the Court notes that the Signature Bond was signed on 10/7/14 
--after hearing arguments from ADA Shock, the Court awards 166 days sentence credit. 
recess 10:54am.

Cases 14CF244 & 14CM262 called together at 1:54 pm [Clerk SH]
Defendant Steven T. Delap in court. DA Susan V. Happ appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Court notes that stand-by Counsel, Atty Huebner is present in gallery. 

Constitutional rights reviewed; maximum penalties recited; plea of "No Contest" entered on Counts #1 & #2-14CM262; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified; Court finds the plea has been entered freely, voluntarily, intelligently and accepts the plea, finds the Defendant  guilty, and orders JOC entered.
On Motion of the State, the Court reads-in and dismisses Count #
3-14CM262 & Case 14CF244

On Counts #1 & #2-14CM262, the Court sentences Mr. Delap to 2 years, with an Initial Term of Confinement in Prison of 1 year and the maximum time to serve on Extended Supervision of 1 year, each count, concurrent. This sentence is to commence 
concurrent to any other previously imposed sentence.

The Court finds that the Defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program (Boot Camp) and the Substance Abuse Program. 
The Court gives 0 days credit for time already served.

The Court orders as conditions of Extended Supervision:
--To pay restitution in amount to be determined at future restitution hearing
--To pay 10% restitution processing fee to be determined at future restitution hearing
--To pay costs of $486 ($243 each count)
--To pay $400 DNA Surcharge ($200 each count)
--To pay Stand-by Attorney fees

Court discharges Attorney Huebner as stand-by counsel on each case & orders Atty Huebner to submit bill in next 2-3 weeks

[Reserve Judge Sarah O'Brien presiding for BrIV]
Defendant Steven T. Delap in court, in custody, with Stand-By Counsel, Attorney Karl Huebner. ADA Monica J Hall appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Court reviews with Mr. Delap signature bonds on file, which have not yet been signed; Mr. Delap informs the Court that he does not wish to sign signature bonds
Court explains to Mr. Delap that a detainer has been placed on him due to him not signing bonds & that he does not receive credit for not signing bonds
Mr. Delap indicates that he will sign bonds as he believed that by not signing bonds he would accrue credit on cases; Court reviews all conditions of bonds with Mr. Delap; Clerk administers bonds to Mr. Delap.

14CF244: Service of the Information admitted; reading waived; maximum penalties recited
Plea of Not Guilty Entered
Court continues bonds as previously set
ADA Hall informs the Court that the State has provided Mr. Delap with an offer
Mr. Delap informs the Court that he would like matters set for trial, but would also like to continue negotiations on matters. Reviews request previously submitted in writing requesting to be housed in Jefferson County.
Parties agree that one day would be needed for trial in each case
Mr. Delap demands speedy trial in both cases, but requests that the misdemeanor case be heard second
Upon questioning of the Court, Mr. Delap indicates that he has no objection to setting misdemeanor matter in January even though it falls outside the speedy trial demand time limits.
Court/ADA Hall review case notes in file which appear to indicate that Mr. Delap waived speedy trial in misdemeanor matter
Mr. Delap confirms that he did waive time speedy trial in misdemeanor matter
ADA Hall presents arguments in opposition of Mr. Delap being housed in Jefferson County Jail
Mr. Delap presents arguments in support of request to be housed in Jefferson County Jail
Court presents basis and denies request of Mr. Delap to be housed in Jefferson County while cases are pending
Court orders that Mr. Delap be in Jefferson County Jail by November 30th so he may have time with Stand-By Counsel before trial
Court charges Clerk to check to be sure detainers are lifted on Mr. Delap since he has sinced his bonds in each case
